{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Valence refers to the degree of pleasure associated with emotions, whereas arousal refers to the intensity of the experienced emotions.",
    "Russell proposed the circumplex model in which emotions formed a circle defined by the dimensions of valence and arousal [27].",
    "In the circumplex model, the subjective experience of pleasure and arousal is called core emotion [28].",
    "Valence and arousal are useful as a basic taxonomy of emotional states [29], however, using only valence and arousal to project a high-dimensional emotional state onto a basic 2D space would result in information loss, for example, some emotions become indistinguishable (e.g., fear and anger), and some emotions are outside the space (e.g., surprise) [30].",
    "Further, Mehrabian [21] extended the emotion model from 2D to 3D to develop a well-known pleasure-arousal-dominance emotion model."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Russell proposed the circumplex model in which emotions formed a circle defined by the dimensions of valence and arousal [27].",
    "In the circumplex model, the subjective experience of pleasure and arousal is called core emotion [28].",
